<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-10-16T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-10-16T18:00:00-05:00" n="230" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d230">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/2185: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-10-17T07:00:00+08:00">October 17, 1931—7
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received 11:16 a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>783. Legation’s 774, October 15, 9 a.m. In reply to inquiry from Hanson
                            [and] Salisbury I have informed them that the Legation assumed it would
                            not be necessary for them to proceed to Chinchow for the present. Does
                            the Department wish them to make an independent investigation of the
                                bombing?<note n="71" xml:id="d230fn71">The Department answered “no”
                                in its telegram No. 387, October 18, 1931, 11 a.m.</note></p>
                        <closer>For the Minister:<lb/><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Engert</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>